segments.text: We were talking about the treatment and the medicine.
Was there ever any danger that, as far as when you're in surgery, that you might have drug addiction at all, or did they keep that regulated?
No.
In fact, now, although I do have a lot of pain, I control the pain
basically with hypnosis.
When did you learn hypnosis?
I picked up on hypnosis in high school and was sort of self-taught and practiced.
Later in college I ran into a doctor there that used hypnosis for childbirth and he led me down a good path.
it became very useful when I was smoke jumping.

I could lay down almost anywhere or hypnotize myself and say I'll wake up in 30 seconds or 5 minutes or whatever and that's during smoke jumping some of the times that was most rest I would get for maybe one or two weeks at a time.
That's good training for when you were in
Yes.
Have you ever seen any patients or know of any patients who have become addicted to drugs while in the VA?
Oh, I know patients that are addicted to drugs that were vying out at the VA, but now where this was caused from the VA or by themselves, I don't know.
Do they have any drug abuse programs for these people at the VA itself, or do they have to go outside?
I don't know, Wally, if they have drug abuse.
I know they have one complete war there that they have for alcoholics, which I believe alcohol is a drug.
So it's, although it's a legal drug, they have a program there, and I know people who are alcoholics, and it's real sad.
As far as your therapy, how did they prepare you for your, you know, to get your artificial leg?
and prosthesis?
Just like any other medical facility would with physical therapy and fitting of the leg and so on and so forth.
I know at that time I had a very difficult time.
I was in traction for three months.
I became allergic to anything that

sticks like I and I was in skin traction so what they would do would put a stockinette around your skin pull the skin down over the bone at the end of the stump and they start out using tincture benzoin or tough skin and I became allergic to that and then surgical easy I can came allergic to that and
and you just have to clean off the leg every day and reapply it and so on.
I think this was mainly because of Agent Orange.
How long was it before you were able to try the prosthesis the first time?
About six months.
What was that experience like the first time you had it on?
Very unusual.
First of all, most people who lose a limb, they think they can put a prosthesis on and just get up and walk away.
But it doesn't happen that way.
I've seen a lot of amputees, and I've never seen one that could do it.

and some people adapt to it very well maybe because of the way their bone structure is and so on and so forth or skin and whatever but I had extremely a lot of difficulty with mine because of skin breakdown and things like this and that is the main reason why I was in the hospital so long was because of this I read something
in one book that I was reading, but I really never understood it.
And that was the subject of what they called phantom pains.
Did this ever occur with you?
I think all amputees have phantom pains.
The medical background is that your nerves that go down the spinal cord are

one long nerve clear down to like your toes or your fingers and if you cut off that nerve then it's cut off but your brain still gets the impulses from that nerve when it's stimulated even though where it's cut off from and although you don't have that limb you can feel things
in that and it feels just like the limb you had.
And this is the reason why is when that nerve is stimulated then you get the same feeling.
Is there ever, do you learn to adapt with it or is it just something that happens?
Well at first you generally have a lot of them and eventually
I think you reprogram your brain to eliminate that.
Now, there is a period, a period of time that maybe you can look and see that one of your limbs are gone, and you know it's gone.
You can feel it so strong that your heart doesn't believe it.
is the way I have to put, and lots of times it took me about three or four months before my heart accepted the fact that it was gone.
When were you released from Brooks?
On what day?
It was in January of 68.
Since that time,
Talking about compensation from the government, has the government made available the funds for you to live comfortably, or have you had any trouble with this?
It's almost a full-time job finding the government for your benefits.
What are the biggest problems that you see in this, the funds?
Right now, I cannot be employed
And under the VA regulations, it says that if you're 60% or more service-connected disability and cannot be employed, then you can get 100% for unemployment.
And I've been finding them for, I guess it's going on five years, to regain my 100%.
I have not succeeded yet.
How can you find them?
What methods do you use?
Well, there's a regular chain that you go through, review boards and so on and so forth.
What is your opinion of these federal agencies who
make the disability evaluations?
In some cases, it's not the federal agency.
I know when I got caught up with it, it was because of the Carter administration.
And before
Jimmy Carter was running for re-election.
He already had in the mail that everybody who was under 55 years of age and was not 100% service-connected disability would be reviewed.
And I got caught up in that review, and I got mine taken away from me.
I have not gotten it back since.
And the funny thing was, just after the election, all these reviews went out immediately after the election.
Have you found that President Reagan has been more helpful, or has the situation improved?
In some degree, it's improved, but maybe because of it.
Now, I'm also...
have disability from Social Security.
And that took a long fight to get that.
But between my military retirement and my Social Security disability that I can live comfortably.
But the difference between 80% and 100% with the VA
is not only a lot of medical benefits, but also there is the difference of approximately $500.
What sort of an insurance plan do you get?
Well, I have a government insurance plan that is
being paid for now.
When I was in the service, there was no government insurance.
You had to buy your own insurance, which I had then.
But since then, since I've had higher disabilities add on, since my injury, that are service-connected, that I was able to get a $10,000 life insurance, which I, as long as I
I'm not employed, the government pays the premiums on this insurance.
Would you rather see it more not national level but more personal level?
How can you do that?
It's been
suggested that the VA system be phased out in favor of a program of insurance credits.
And I don't know if you've heard about this or not, but I ran across it in the Ralph Nader report.
Do you think this might be a better alternative than the present VA system?
No, I think it would be worse.
Why is that?
Well, because
Well, I understand under that, that would be fall under Medicare.
And then, like, when I go up for service-connected disabilities at the hospital, I don't have to pay any money for it whatsoever.
But under Medicare, you do.
You have a regular premium, you have deductible, and it only takes a certain amount of things and for a certain length of time.
and say like I can only go up and have a certain number of appointments for a ailment, say like my stump that breaks down constantly and I have infections in it constantly.
What Medicare plan is,
that they take a average of all the people, and then they say, OK, the average is this, so you can have up to this.
And that eliminates any individuality whatsoever, where my stump is constantly breaking down and with infections, but yet I get the same benefits
I will be limited to my benefits when somebody else's would not break down whatsoever.
So you feel the VA is more of a personal type of thing?
Well, I wouldn't say yes would be much more personal than what Medicare and their Social Security would be or a program like that.
And what is even more personal is your military hospitals, which I have access to right now also.
So here in San Antonio, I have three large hospitals.
I can go for medical care free right now.
Can't beat that.
It's 15 years now to society.
How do you feel about the rest of society in general?
I've read where a lot of Vietnam veterans have differing views.
Well, I think that's the same with any cross-section of the American population.
I've read where a lot of people are cynical.
Do you ever feel any cynicism towards the society at all?
No, but I think there's a lot of truth in it that I've heard a lot of veterans say that when they apply for a job that they can't get because they're a Vietnam veteran.
Now whether this is true or not, I don't know.
Besides the obvious adjustments you had to make, what sort of changes did you notice when you got back from Vietnam?
Well, I had to change my whole lifestyle because I was a very avid skier, racer, mountain climbing, and I used to skydive and so on.
my whole outlook I had to change.
I had to make a complete change of lifestyle.
What did you find helped you the most in helping you cope with your disability?
I don't know, I guess it's just like I said before, it's either inbred or it's not.
Just a will to go on.
How did, do you think, what was the effect of the Army on you?
Did the service change you in any way?
No, I don't think so.
How has war, just war itself, changed your outlook on life, or has it?
Well, I don't go hunting anymore.
I used to like to hunt.
Maybe I have some part of a feeling of what it's like to be shot at.
It changes your outlook that way.
In the late 1960s, these are all just a lot of little general questions that I just had and couldn't, found trouble fitting them in.
In the late 1960s, a lot of, mostly the youth, college students and whatnot, started opposing our involvement in the Vietnam War.
What was your feelings towards the protest movements?
I think they have a right to protest, but I don't think they have a right to infringe on the other person's freedoms under the Constitution.
And I think they were doing this.
Were you ever confronted by any of the Vietnam veterans against the war organizations at all?
No, I've stayed clear.

Like normally, your normal veterans organizations such as your VFW and American Legion, I don't normally approve of them because the only thing they are is a place where they'll get drunk, the way I feel.
And that's not the right way of doing things.
You had mentioned that you're in the Special Forces organization in this Alamo chapter.
Talk a little bit about that.
What is the objectives of this organization?
To be of service to the community and to bring people together who had the same camaraderie during the war.
We are active in that.
We're trying to become active in a volunteer program up at the VA hospital.
And we have set up a scholarship fund for children of the special forces or the ones who died in Vietnam.
to help them through, we're trying to set up a scholarship fund for that.

And we believe in the American way, Constitution, and you might say we're more a military-like organization that, like on the veterans parades and so on, we try to participate in, and we do this quite a bit.
Have you found in your community services, have you found that the community has been receptive?
Well, we aren't big enough yet to really find out, but I feel what little feedback we have is that it's very positive.
That's great.
Now, one thing coming up in, I believe, October, we're going to have 5K runs.
Fort Sam, and we're throwing a little extra twist in it.
For the people who want to, they can go through a pretty good obstacle course with the run.
Oh, gosh.
Test your endurance.
You're right.
How are you all funded, basically?
From news.
So you all don't get any really outside help at all?
No.
The dues and gifts from different people.
I have two last questions, and they're very personal questions.
Do you feel, looking back at it now, was the Vietnam War worthwhile to you?
Yes.
tensions mounting up in Central America and the Middle East and abroad.
What is your opinion of war itself?
Well, I believe that we should defend our country and our allies.
That's all the questions I have and I really thank you a lot.
You've been a
tremendous inspiration to me and I think anybody who you know and talk to.
And in closing, I was wondering if there's anything you'd like to say.
No.
Thank you very much.
You're welcome.
